valuesByForeignRowId.recVctkr0WJNJU88n:
Before getting into crypto, I cofounded a community called Sail, whose mission was to help guys become more vulnerable and emotionally intelligent. We ran group-coaching programs and weekly activities for hundreds of men throughout the pandemic, and eventually were acquired by Maven in Summer of 2021. Through this period, I discovered my purpose: to build products that empower communities.

Im inspired by the power that synchronous experiences can have on communities. The best way, I think, to grow strong communities is by bringing people together, giving them a purpose, and letting real relationships form from there.

Im also inspired by Ethereum, which I describe first and foremost as a social network. When I was in business school, I got to talk with the founders of Venmo and they told me that the key to Venmos success was that it was actually a social network. The transactions people send are a proxy for what they do, and who they do it with. Ethereum is like that, except much more powerful. I ask the question: how will a social network of status, that we all own, that runs under every app, change how we communicate and organize? The answer is a lot.

Finally, the project that brings me here is Eventcaster. If Ethereum is a social network, then the tagline for this project is Facebook Events for Ethereum. Its a community-centric events platform, completely crypto-native. It does for events what Snapshot has done for voting that is to say, create a single source of truth to check, that can automatically be pushed everywhere a community lives.
Mem Protocol is building tools for the social layer of web3.

valuesByForeignRowId.rec5UKSOGefA0jPZt:
I am someone who has always been obsessed with new things: innovation, technology, food, cultures, and change. I largely attribute this to how I've grown up. I'm from Hong Kong, but spent first 8 years of my life in Toronto and then moved to Guangzhou in mainland China until high school. Having lived in China during the peak of it's economic growth, I saw firsthand how technology impacted not just the economy but also culture and consumer behavior. I witnesses the growth of superapps like WeChat and platforms like Alibaba take over. At the time, I was very influenced by my parents who were early adopters and investors of every technological trend because they really believed in the long-term vision many of these new companies brought. While most of their friends were always slow to adopt ecommerce or new ideas, my parents doubled down and made a career building companies in this space. 

Fast forward to college, I moved to the Bay Area where innovation was at the core of everything. In college, we would get pitched all sorts of new startup ideas as students on campus. Free delivery services, discounted work out classes, gamified cloud storage systems, discounted car rides back from formal events. Many of my classmates found these ads and companies to be annoying and always ignored the fliers on campus... but I had always been someone who tried everything once. Little did I know most of these startups that I tried were actually just seed-stage companies at the time... desperately trying to find product market fit among college students. While 80% of the companies I tried ended up winding down, the rest of them became large venture-backed companies like Uber, Dropbox, Classpass, and Doordash, and I had always been an avid early supporter and ambassador of them all. 

Many years later, little did I know that I would make a career out of trying new things... and similar to my parents, try to see the long-term vision of what something "could be."
